  "prompt": "What does the @ symbol do in Excel?",
  "response": "In Microsoft Excel, the @ symbol is used primarily in structured references for Excel tables, representing implicit intersection. This often appears when you're working with formulas inside Excel tables. Here\u2019s a detailed explanation of its usage:\n\n### Structured References\n\nWhen you create a table in Excel, each column can have its own header, and you can reference these headers in formulas. The @ symbol is used to refer to the data in the same row as the formula, within the column mentioned. \n\nFor example, if you have an Excel table with columns \"Product\", \"Sales\", and \"Cost\", and you want to calculate the \"Profit\" for each row, you could use a formula like:\n```\n=[@Sales] - [@Cost]\n```\n\nIn this context:\n- `[@Sales]` refers to the \"Sales\" value in the current row.\n- `[@Cost]` refers to the \"Cost\" value in the current row.\n\n### Implicit intersection\n\nThe @ symbol in formulas ensures Excel uses the correct cell in the current row. Before Excel 2021 and the dynamic array update, it wasn't as explicitly visible. However, in versions adopting dynamic arrays, explicit \u201c@\u201d symbols began appearing more frequently in converted formulas to maintain backward compatibility.\n\n### Example Scenario\n\nIf you have a table with these data:\n\n| Product  | Sales | Cost  |\n|----------|-------|-------|\n| A        | 500   | 300   |\n| B        | 700   | 400   |\n| C        | 600   | 350   |\n\nTo compute the profit in a column named \"Profit\", you could add this formula:\n```\n=[@Sales] - [@Cost]\n```\n\nFor each row, this formula calculates the difference between \"Sales\" and \"Cost\" in the same row.\n\n### Not for Email Addresses\n\nIt\u2019s worth noting that while the @ symbol is commonly associated with email addresses (e.g., user@example.com), in Excel, it serves a different purpose related to referencing table data.\n\nUnderstanding the use of \"@\" helps ensure your formulas in tables are dynamically referencing the correct data as intended.",
